how to handle a puppy mill rescue puppy after you bring him home i recently found a month old bichon frise puppy at a humane society i haven't gotten him yet and its not sure that i will be able to have him i do have him on reserve just for me i haven't gotten to see him because they want to tempermant test him and get him fixed before they call me they said he was shy but should warm up quickly when and if i do get to adopt him what could i expect i also really want to crate train him but will that make scared i don't want to remind him of the puppy mill but i don't want him messing all over the house i really need some advice i have had experience with pups from mills and it will go one of two ways he'll be terrified or he'll be desperate for affection one thing that will help him along will be how he's treated by the humane society staff they have a tendancy to really love up on the saddest cases so you may be all set when you get him as for the crate training if you're worried try a small room like a bathroom or laundry area and one of those really good plastic kiddie gates get a product called wee wee pads from a pet supplier and you can start housebreaking him that way on a good note bichon's or bitchin' freezes as a vet friend used to refer to them are very intelligent and they love to please the special human in their life you shouldn't have too much trouble and bravo for adopting instead of buying from a breeder Housebreaking Havanese Dog training Crate training Dog Pet skunk Socialization Shaggy dog story Theory of conduct Guinea pig RuneScape quests Ron and Fez Social rule Golden Retriever The Smoking Room Scooby-Doo Hamster Labrador Retriever Fancy rat Friends Avenue Q Pitaten Puppy mill Sin City Skinny Puppy Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan The Death Gate Cycle Bichon Fris__ Kitchen Love Hina main characters Episodes of Lost (Season 1) Domestic rabbit Characters in the Smurfs One Tree Hill (TV series) M16 (rifle) Girly Charles Goodyear Kevin and Kell Hum